edecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"the","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Dorothea  , also used independently."],"variants":[]},{"name":"First","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Greek <i>Thyrsos</i>.  See  <b>Tirso</b>   ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Governor of Caen Robert the First de Gouvis was born in 1090, in Caen, Calvados, Normandy, France, his father, Harold de Vaux Pentney de Gouvis, was 25 and his mother, Beatrice Muncheny, was 25. He married Lady Hawise de Reviers in 1115, in Gloucestershire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"1090–":"1090–Surnud","1090–Male":"1090–Surnud","1090–Female":"1090–Surnud","1149–1229":"1149–1229","1065–Male":"1065–Surnud","1065–Female":"1065–Surnud","1090":"1090","1115 to 1149":"1115","1149":"1149","1065":"1065","1229":"1229","Dewich, Dorsetshire, England":"Dorset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Caen, Calvados, Normandy, France":"Caen, Calvados, Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Gloucestershire, England and Carn France":"Gloucestershire, England"},"fi":{"1090–":"1090–Kuollut","1090–Male":"1090–Kuollut","1090–Female":"1090–Kuollut","1149–1229":"1149–1229","1065–Male":"1065–Kuollut","1065–Female":"1065–Kuollut","1090":"1090","1115 to 1149":"1115","1149":"1149"